- "Just" would be totally objective application of the Law. Judges would have no power to 'commute' or increase sentances.  Penalties would be known and applied once guilt of a charge was assertained.  Equality of Race, Religion, Financial status and so on would be necessary.  This would be extemely difficult if not impossible.  Its funny, America is such a wonderful country.  We have overcome several major hurdles towards this 'just' society.  The Rule of Law is the key to this success.  Our greatest challenge lay before us, but its a challenge I dont know we can solve at this time.  The problem of 'Have and Have Nots' is a real problem.  The lower dregs of society suffering due to a lack of proper and aggressive defense before the Law is a problem. /shrug A problem I dont know we will ever solve.  Judges getting to change the sentancing for a crime really pisses me off.  Its nice for movies, but in RL it sucks Hard.<br>
<br>
2) What country (or state or province of a country) most closely resembles your utopia? Even still what changes what you have that region make?<br>
- American 2002, without a doubt.  No other government has come close to the respect for universal human dignity, empowerment of the poor and underpriveleged and aggressive defense of the rights of its citizens.  OH there are problems, Huge ones.  Largely centered on the bureaucratic system surrounding that government.  The two party system also has problems.  Largely 'historic' or bureaucratic ones.  We have the weight of generations of ideas pressing on really smart, really good people, forcing them to take stupid positions so that they can get the money to get elected.  A good example of this is Al Gore Versus BillClinton.  Gore 'believed' strongly in the party line and the socio-economic plans he wanted to implement.  Clinton believed only in success.  He said whatever the majority of the people wanted to hear.  This will take you very far in our world.  But the price is high.  Clinton as a Republican would have cut a VERY interesting figure.  Gore would never fit in that box, but Clinton easily could.  I am not saying Clinton was all bad, but I am saying that the two party system has really screwed up the conversations that we should be having about good person to rule the world.  I refuse to believe that the ruler of the world should be limited into Repulican or Democratic shoes.  There has to be another way.  Not simply a third party, but a new way as a whole.  Something where neither party or any party gets money from the government.  I honestly dont know the answer to this one.<br>
<br>
