On the other hand, the murderer who gets executed will never murder again, and I do appreciate that argument. But life without parole is a very harsh and effective punishment. <p><img src="http://squirming.net/meme/tests/criminal/elizabethbathory.jpg" title="I am Elizabeth Bathory."><br \><a href="http://squirming.net/meme/tests/criminal/">Which Evil Criminal are <i>You</i>?</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E6E6CC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub92.ezboard.com/uzantoz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zantoz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Centered One</span><br>  Posts: 208<br> <font color=#000000>(1/10/02 2:11:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub92.ezboard.com/fmystiquessoulfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=138.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.looroll.com/thesheets/wallpapers/m/manifestation_thumb.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Death Penalty</span><hr size=1> I am against the death penalty for two reasons:<br>
<br>
1. Killing is wrong.<br>
2. Human error<br>
<br>
1.<br>
"Killing is wrong" is a moral stance which alot of us agree on.  We see that the ending of another person's life is not a good thing.  This is not only because of some hope that if we treat others well, they will treat us well. (ie. I dont kill you, you wont kill me.) But rather, this life is all we know.  Whatever belief I have about the post-life events, they are simply that, beliefs.  This is the only world we can all agree on exists.<br>
<br>
The State should not kill its members because this 'violates' the contract that exists between the State and the Citizen.  One can argue that the Citizen that violates the rights of another Citizen forfeits their own rights.  That is a valid stance.  This then allows the State to end the life of the Offending Citizen.<br>
<br>
But, in my opinion, the actions of a Citizen does not change the 'properties' of the Citizen.  A Citizen is a Citizen is a Citizen.  Each Citizen should have the same rights as the other Citizens.  That said, clearly some reasonable steps must be taken to protect the 'innocent' Citizens from the criminal Citizen.  The 'protection' should be 'reasonable and appropriate'.<br>
<br>
The killer Citizen cannot be trusted to exist with other Citizens.  He/she should be removed from the general population to protect 'innocent' Citizens.  This is like padding a cell so that an insane person does not hurt themselves.  You are not padding the cell to torture or get revenge on the patient, you are trying to protect them.  Likewise, removal from the 'innocent' Citizen pool protects without the motive of revenge.  "I am not doing this to punish you.  I am doing this to protect my Citizens."<br>
<br>
"Killing is wrong" can not only be applied toward death penalties but towards war as well.  When a conflict arises, one party wants to inflict their will on another.  They attempt to do this using 'power.'  Power of bomb, power of gun, power of stick and stone.  In war, the objective is not to kill the enemy, but to remove their power.  They can possess the will to hurt me, but if they have no power to do so, then I am safe. (True, it is better to change the will, but I am not talking about policy of relationship, but rather the act of war.)<br>
This is an ideal.  An ideal which is hard/impossible to realize.  But I think it is something we should aim for.  You can only go as far as you aim.  I think we need to raise our sights.<br>
<br>
Everywhere I look I see "God Bless America."  I agree with this.  Then I see CNN footage of soliders, putting writing on bombs saying "Up yours Osama."  I wonder if this is revenge or justice.  I wonder if this is the tactical application of power to remove the power of the enemy or is this the application of power to kill alot of the people we hate today.  But I digress.<br>
<br>
The State should not kill it Citizens because to do so, we tell our children it is okay to kill sometimes, we tell the world that we are killers of our own people, we tell ourselves that we are 'better' than 'that other guy in the box'.  We stand in moral, mortal judgement over people who, but for the grace of God we would be.  The line is grey and blurred between what you would kill for and what I would kill for. Some would kill for treason.  Some would kill for drug dealing.  Some would kill for murder.  The Will of the State is made up two things: 1. The Constitution underwhich it was created, and 2. The current Will of the People.<br>
<br>
The State should speak to 'the greater angels of our nature.' And not the vengful, fearful heart./1.<br>
<br>
2. People make mistakes.  Executions cannot be undone.  If even one person is killed wrongly, then the system collapses.  The safest course of action is to kill no one.  I am a safe player./2.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
In conclusion, while it is hard on the State to keep alive the long term killer, if a true cost analysis was made of how much it costs to fight a death penalty, I think that we would find the killer is costing us alot more to kill than to keep around in a cell.  The killer can be made to work for their keep.  The killer can be taught skills which can then be used to help society.  The killer can work to make up for, somehow, the death of the person they killed.  Once the killer is killed the 'karma balance' ends.  There is no chance of understanding or redress.  There is no chance of change of heart.  All we will have done is had two deaths instead of one.<br>
<br>
Our hearts have brtuals animals in them.  I know I have one in there.  I want to rend the flesh from Osamar.  I want to carpet bomb various areas around the world.  I want to see the screaming burning bodies of the people that bombed my country.  I want revenge......<br>
<br>
But I can't have that.  I can't have my revenge and my high moral ground.  I can't have revenge and dignity.  I can't be the devil of my nature and the better angel of my nature.  I can't drink the blood of my enemy and turn to my chilren, bloody lipped, and say, "Be like me.  I love you.  Love others."<br>
<br>
<br>
Seriously deep and perhaps a bit screwed up, but that is me.<br>
<br>
Peace,<br>
<br>
Zan<br>
